Mr. Stankiewicz is a 45-year-old gentleman who presents for treatment of distal rectal cancer.  Mr. Stankiewicz normally enjoys good health until he developed hematochezia in May 2010.  His first colonoscopy June 14, 2010, was positive for a 4- to 5-mm polyp removed from the left colon at 70 cm (lost), and a fungating mass was noted in the distal rectum, described 3-cm above the anal verge.  Biopsies were taken, demonstrated grade 2 (of 4) adenocarcinoma as described by Conley Hospital.  A CT abdomen and pelvis showed a prominent mass in the rectum but no evidence of lymphadenopathy or metastatic disease.  Mr. Stankiewicz denies any other complaints including no nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, weight-loss, fever, melena, diarrhea, constipation, change in bowel habit, or rectal pain, or narrowed stool caliber.  His family history is negative for colorectal neoplasia.
His only chronic comorbidity is seasonal allergies, for which he uses occasional Claritin.  There is no history of cardiopulmonary symptoms or complaints, including no chest pain, pressure, discomfort, shortness-of-breath, dizziness, lightheadedness, weakness, or fatigue.  There is no history of bleeding disorder, anesthesia reaction, thrombosis, heart attack, stroke, glaucoma, sleep apnea, or malignant hypothermia.

